## Q26
Question:
The following are examples of Einstein's mass energy equivalence theory:
Option A:
Annihilation radiation
Option B:
Pair production
Option C:
Nuclear fission
Option D:
All of the above
Correct Answer:
D
Difficulty:
Medium
Explanation:
Einstein’s mass-energy equivalence equation (E=mc^2) states that mass and energy are interchangeable. Annihilation radiation (where mass converts to energy), pair production (where energy converts to mass), and nuclear fission (where mass defect converts to huge energy) are all practical, observable proofs of this fundamental principle.
